    "summary": "Pi\u00ebrre van de Laar was born in Bavel, the Netherlands, in 1971. Between 1989 and 1998 he studied at the Catholic University of Nijmegen and was awarded his master degree (cum laude) in both theoretical and computational physics in 1994 and his PhD on 'Selection in Neural Information Processing' in 1999.\n\nFrom 1998 until 2006, he was employed by Philips Research in Eindhoven. He spent the first two years following the course 'from doctor in science to computational scientist'. From 2000 onwards, he investigated the exploitation of architecture description languages for product families, visualization, verification, aspect-orientation, and dependability.\n\nSince 2006, he has been employed by the Embedded Systems Institute as a Research Fellow. \nHe participated in \n* a study for DaimlerChrysler;\n* Darwin, a collaborative research project between the Embedded Systems Institute,\nPhilips, and five Dutch universities that improved the evolvability of complex systems as described in https://doi.org/10.1007/978-90-481-9849-8; \n* Poseidon, a collaborative research project between the Embedded Systems Institute, Thales, Noldus, and five Dutch universities that built situation awareness in systems of systems as described in  https://doi.org/10.1007/978-1-4614-6230-9; \n* Metis, a collaborative research project between the Embedded Systems Institute, Thales, and four Dutch universities that incorporated uncertain information for improved situation awareness; \n* Themis, an ASML research project that supersized model-based testing, including test data generation, resulting in TorXakis, available at https://github.com/TorXakis/TorXakis;\n* Bright, an ITEC (Nexperia) research project that rejuvenated software written in Ada, resulting in the Ada crates available at https://github.com/TNO/Renaissance-Ada; and\n* Poka Yoke, a collaborative research project between the TNO ESI, ASML, and VDL-ETG on synthesis-based engineering using formal specifications.\n\nSpecialties: embedded systems research, product families, visualization of software archives, evolvability, situation awareness, systems-of-systems, model-based testing, rejuvenation, analysis and transformation",
